<subSubSection pageId="128" pageNumber="129" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="128.[189,745,1528,1620]" box="[189,310,1594,1620]" pageId="128" pageNumber="129">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,1594,1620]" pageId="128" pageNumber="129">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="128.[189,1399,1640,1914]" pageId="128" pageNumber="129">
Species with wholly black thorax. Palpus yellow. Thorax black. Legs almost wholly yellow, only tarsomere 5 of all legs black. Mid femur with 3 moderately long, brownish ventral bristles in basal 1/3. Wing deeper infuscate along R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[565,591,1729,1743]" fontSize="6" pageId="128" pageNumber="129">4+5</subScript>
and CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[706,715,1729,1743]" fontSize="6" pageId="128" pageNumber="129">1</subScript>
; R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[753,780,1729,1743]" fontSize="6" pageId="128" pageNumber="129">2+3</subScript>
nearly 3.0 times longer than Rs. Distance between apices of R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[327,354,1765,1779]" fontSize="6" pageId="128" pageNumber="129">2+3</subScript>
and R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[437,464,1764,1778]" fontSize="6" pageId="128" pageNumber="129">4+5</subScript>
somewhat longer than distance between apices of R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1103,1112,1765,1779]" fontSize="6" pageId="128" pageNumber="129">1</subScript>
and R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1194,1227,1765,1779]" fontSize="6" pageId="128" pageNumber="129">2+3.</subScript>
R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1256,1282,1764,1778]" fontSize="6" pageId="128" pageNumber="129">4+5</subScript>
and M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1372,1399,1765,1779]" fontSize="6" pageId="128" pageNumber="129">1+2</subScript>
divergent and evenly arcuate in apical part. Abdominal gland-like structures not prominent. Male terminalia lacking spines, upper lobe of left surstylus with markedly developed surstylar comb. Female similar to male except, mid femur with 3 longer, yellow ventral bristles and mid tibia lacking black ventral spinules.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
